    <title>Combined summary - Version bytes "2.0"</title>
    <updated>2023-06-04T21:47:27.404632+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2011-December/000809.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The context revolves around various proposals and issues concerning the Bitcoin specification, with a particular focus on usability. One proposal suggests changing the base58 encoding to improve the recognizability of different data classes. Another proposes creating an easy-to-use UI for generating payment links using copy/paste and drag/drop functionality. The appearance of Bitcoin addresses is also discussed, with some suggesting that creating links containing a bitcoin: URL would be more beneficial than focusing on address appearance. In addition to these proposals, there are several other ideas put forward. The first proposal aims to define the network class using bits 128/64 to solve issues with public and private keys starting with the same characters. Another proposal suggests using different bits to define network class, network, and data class for script-based addresses. A revised proposal for making a Bitcoin-compatible Namecoin address has also been put forward, defining different bits for network class and network, as well as data class options.Furthermore, a proposal has been made to remove the "version" notion from version bytes in base58 encoding to improve recognizability of data classes. In December 2011, Pieter Wuille wrote an email discussing the use of base58 for producing human-recognizable addresses. He suggested that base58 was not good for this purpose and proposed using 20-byte base58 for now and overhauling it in the future. The proposed encoding included mainnet pubkey hashes as '1', testnet pubkey hashes as '2', mainnet script hashes as '3', and testnet script hashes as '2'. For mainnet private keys, the proposal suggested using 'Q', 'R' or 'S' instead of 128 and using '7' instead of 239 for testnet private keys.</summary>
